        <name>ICE OUT: COMMUNITY VIGIL | Saugatuck</name>
        <description><![CDATA[
<h3>ICE OUT: COMMUNITY VIGIL | Saugatuck</h3>
<p><strong>When:</strong> Sunday, March 1, 2026 at 10:30 PM UTC - 11:30 PM</p>
<p><strong>Where:</strong><br>All Saints Episcapol Church<br>252 Grand St<br>Saugatuck, MI 49453</p>
<p><strong>Organized by:</strong> Indivisible</p>
<p><strong>About:</strong></p><p>ICE OUT COMMUNITY VIGIL – A Space for Witness, Grief, and Collective Voice

Host Organization:
Good Trouble Indivisible (with community partners)

📍All Saints Episcopal Church (indoors)
     252 Grand St, Saugatuck, MI 49453
(All Saints supports our movement and donates the use of their space to us free of charge!)

📆 Every Sunday Evening 

⏰ 5:30 PM – 6:30 PM | Please allow additional time for a quiet, respectful departure by 7:00 PM.

Event Description:
This is a community-led ICE OUT vigil. The word vigil is a period of keeping awake (or aware), especially to keep watch; a stationary, peaceful demonstration in support of a particular cause, typically without speeches.
We have created our ICE OUT VIGIL as an audience-led space for reflection about the atrocities ICE commits daily, and the crumbling of our democracy and our Rule-Of-Law. We share our grief for lives shattered and lives lost and our thoughts about the continuing chaos and destruction our country. 

This gathering is non-partisan and open to all. People of all backgrounds, beliefs, and political affiliations are welcome. The focus of this vigil is humanitarian, moral, and grounded in shared human dignity.

There will be no featured speakers and no formal program. Instead, the vigil centers the voices of those who attend. Community members are invited to stand and speak from the pulpit or from their seats, sharing how they feel about ICE enforcement practices, including detention, deportation, family separation, brutality, and loss of life; as well as the upending of our freedoms. 

This is a space to:

	•	Speak truth

	•	Use your voice

	•	Sit with one another in reflection and conversation 


A light facilitation will help maintain a respectful, grounded flow, but the vigil itself belongs to the community.

What to Expect:

	•	Indoor, seated vigil

	•	Quiet, respectful atmosphere

	•	Community sharing (voluntary)

	•	No microphones or amplification

	•	No chanting or movement outside the sanctuary

	•	Hand-Raising and 3 minute talk limit per person to give everyone the opportunity to be heard. (No limit as to how many times you can speak) Please do not talk over others and wait for your turn to be called-on once your hand is raised. The facilitator will do their best to go in order of first hands raised. 


What This Is / Is Not:

	✔ A vigil, ✖ not a protest

	✔ Non-partisan and community-centered

	✔ Open and welcoming to all

	✔ A space for moral witness and shared humanity

	✖ Not a rally or planning meeting

All are welcome who come in the spirit of respect, reflection, and care for one another.

⸻

Good Trouble Indivisible is a Michigan nonprofit corporation
Action@goodtroubleindivisible.org
(616) 287-2221

⸻

This a local Indivisible event hosted by GOOD TROUBLE INDIVISIBLE; Saugatuck-Douglas Uniting West Michigan.

*A core principle behind all Indivisible events is a commitment to nonviolent action. We expect all participants to seek to de-escalate any potential confrontation with those who disagree with our values.*</p>
